dataset.title: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities, Montane Meadows as Indicators of Hydrologic Change, 2010-2012, Cedar River Municipal Watershed, King County, WA

creator.organizationName: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities

abstract.para: Detecting effects of climate change is typically done using physical measurements such as spring snow water equivalent or stream flow, but these metrics do not address ecosystem effects of climate change. A potential surrogate for reduced summer streamflow and soil moisture in the Cedar River Municipal Watershed (CRMW) are wet meadows that are fed by melting snow and shallow groundwater in the headwaters of several major streams. Saturated soils through most, if not all, of the growing season in these montane meadows support a rich assemblage of mostly herbaceous wetland plant species and exclude upland species. Species composition and abundance in wet meadows would likely change if reductions in snowpack and a longer summer dry season resulted in drier meadow soils. Wet meadows are essentially intermediate storage sites for water flowing through the watershed and are predicted to respond biologically in detectible ways should their hydrology change. Such changes could occur relatively quickly (3-10 years), as short-lived plant tissues (one to two years typically) allow for rapid plant community response to changes in resource levels.

description.para: Study design: three groups of montane meadows sampled for plant community composition and hydrologic characteristics. One group was meadows surrounded by old growth forest and the second and third group are meadows surrounded by young second growth forest, with one of the second growth forests available for thinning and one to be used as a control for evaluating effects of thinning. A total of 12 meadows were sampled, four from each of the three groups described. Meadows were located in the upper Rex River, Lindsay Creek, and Fish Creek subbasins.

Sampling of meadow vegetation will be designed to characterize current variability within and among meadows and to establish baseline conditions for comparison to future conditions. The plant community sampling methodology utilized four permanently marked transects per meadow that were located across the extent of each meadow, with five sampling locations systematically arrayed along each of the transects. Species cover and frequency was quantified at each sampling location, resulting in 20 samples per meadow.

Water levels measured in wells: five wells were established in each fen, one near the center and the other four near the periphery of the sample area along each side, providing a profile of three wells along each axis of the sample area block. Wells were constructed by augering a 5-centimeter diameter hole into the peat deposits and inserting a 5-centimeter diameter PVC pipe perforated with 6-millimeter diameter holes. Water table depth was determined by measuring the depth to water from the top of the well and subtracting the well height above the ground surface. All wells were installed to at least 86-centimeters depth and most were >1-meter depth. Wells were monitored every three weeks until later September or early October through the 2010, 2011, and 2012 growing seasons.

Soil moisture: within quadrat locations, volumetric water content was measured to quantify variability in rooting zone soil moisture across the fens during the driest part of the summer. The measurements were made on 29-30 August 2011 toward the end of the summer dry season using a soil moisture probe (HydroSense Soil Water Measurement System) inserted to a depth of 12-centimeters. Precipitation over the previous month prior to the measurements totaled 25-millimeters, with 23 of that falling in one storm a week previous. Five readings per quadrat were made, in the same subquadrat locations as the plant cover measurements, and averaged over the quadrat. The instrument output was calibrated to highly organic soils by progressively drying and weighing two fen soil samples to determine volumetric water content gravimetrically at intervals through the dry-down process.

Vegetation cover data for meadow plots: within each fen, 28 to 35 1-meter squared quadrats were established within a block of three to seven transects, with the distance between quadrats generally ranging from 4 to 7 meters. In all fens at least two sides of the transect blocks were sampled out to the shrub or tree margin. The transect blocks occupied areas ranging from .08 to .13 hectare, which was from 8 to 28 percent of the total area of each fen. Quadrat locations were established and relocated using transect posts constructed of rebar with a meter tape strung tightly between them. The quadrats were delineated by a 1-meter squared frame constructed from PVC pipe that was marked to define ten 20 x 50-centimeter cells. Within every other cell, percent cover of all vascular plant species was estimated within a 20 x 50-centimeter subquadrat frame constructed from PVC pipe. The quadrat cover values were the average of the five subsample estimates, which were all collected by one observer in August to early September, 2010. Plant species nomenclature follows that of the USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service PLANTS Database.

Transpiration data for each plot: within the same quadrat locations, estimates of canopy and light environment were made in early September 2011 by taking a photograph of the sky and surrounding forest canopy using a hemispherical lens (Sigma 4.5 millimeter) on a digital SLR camera (Canon EOS Digital Rebel). The camera lens was leveled and positioned at the center of the 1-meter squared quadrat at a height of 1-meter, and an exposure was made with an f-stop of 8.0 with shutter speed varied to provide an exposure that has two stops more open than the exposure meter reading for open sky. The images were processed using the Gap Light Analyzer (GLA) v 2.0 software, following guidelines in the GLA user manual. The percent open canopy and direct and total (direct plus diffuse) radiation integrated over the period May 1 to September 31 were used to quantify the variability in light environment across the sampled fen area as affected by the surrounding forest canopy and adjacent slopes.

project.title: Montane Meadows as Indicators of Hydrologic Change in the CRMW

personnel.organizationName: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities

abstract.para: This study has two general goals. The first is to assess the need for specific restoration thinning treatments around montane meadows in the Cedar River Municipal Watershed. The second is to use montane meadows as an indicator for a long-term monitoring of climate change impacts on watershed ecosystems.

Montane meadows are an important element of biodiversity in the Cedar River Municipal Watershed, representing unique aquatic and riparian habitat within a largely forested landscape. If timber harvest of surrounding forest has negatively impacted these meadows, forest restoration treatments around these meadows should be designed to hasten recovery of conditions that will reverse meadow impacts. This project will assess the impacts of timber harvest on montane wet meadows in the watershed to determine if timber harvest has led to changes in plant species composition and abundance. These results will then be used to inform the design of restoration thinning treatments in surrounding forest.

Because many montane wet meadows are supported by emerging groundwater, they are likely to be sensitive in relatively short time-frames to potential impacts of climate change on watershed hydrology. Consequently, they have strong potential as indicators of hydrologic change brought about by warmer winters, reduced snowpack, and warmer summers that are expected to occur as climate changes in coming decades. The sites sampled and data collected for assessing timber harvest impacts can also serve as baseline conditions for a long-term monitoring program to detect ecosystem-level changes resulting from climate change. Such an early-warning indicator of watershed climate impacts would be extremely valuable in planning adaptive responses to broader watershed impacts from climate change.
